.TH DXmCreateCursor 3X
.SH NAME
\*LDXmCreateCursor\*O \- Creates a specific cursor.
.SH SYNOPSIS
.PP
.iX "DXmCreateCursor"
.sS
\*LCursor DXmCreateCursor(\*Vwidget\*L, \*Vcursorkind\*L)
        Widget  \*Vwidget\*L;
        int     \*Vcursorkind\*L;\*O
.sE
.SH PARAMETERS
.PP
.VL 4m
.LI "\*Vwidget\*O"
The widget from which display information is obtained.
.LI "\*Vcursorkind\*O"
An integer that represents the type of cursor, as follows:
.IP
.TS
tab(@);
lfHB lfHB
l l .
_
.sp
Value@Cursor Description
.sp
_
.sp
decw$c_wait_cursor (4)@T{
A watch
T}
.sp
decw$c_questionmark_cursor (54)@T{
A question mark
T}
.sp
decw$c_inactive_cursor (6)@T{
A caution ("do not enter") symbol
T}
.sp
_
.TE
.ne 3i
.IP
The following X Window System fallbacks are provided in the event the
DECwindows-specific cursors cannot be loaded:
.IP
.TS
tab(@);
lfHB lfHB
l l .
_
.sp
DECwindows-Specific Cursor@X Fallback
.sp
_
.sp
decw$c_wait_cursor@T{
XC_watch
T}
.sp
decw$c_questionmark_cursor@T{
XC_question_arrow
T}
.sp
decw$c_inactive_cursor@T{
XC_circle
T}
.sp
_
.TE
.IP
You can specify additional cursor symbols by examining the
\*L/usr/include/X11/decwcursor.h\*O file.  (X Window System
fallbacks are provided for each of those cursors as well.)
.LE
.SH DESCRIPTION
.PP
The \*LDXmCreateCursor\*O routine enables you to create a cursor that
displays as a watch, question mark, or caution ("do not enter") symbol
(these are the most frequently used cursor symbols).
.SH RETURN VALUES
.PP
The identifier (cursor ID) of the created cursor.
.EQ
delim off
.EN
